The divergent term term of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}(t)$
\end_inset 

 can be immediately integrated to obtain the divergent term in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{c}(t)$
\end_inset 

 inside the cardiod: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{c}(t)=\frac{1}{t}\;\left[\frac{1}{2}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}-c}\;\right]+\mathcal{O}(1)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 If we write this divergent piece as 
\begin_inset Formula $A(c)=\frac{1}{2}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}-c}$
\end_inset 

 then it is trivial to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $|A(c)|=1/2$
\end_inset 

 on the boundary of the cardiod; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $|A(e^{i\phi/2}-e^{2i\phi}/4)|=1/2$
\end_inset 

 for all angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

.
 The boundary of the cardiod is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x+iy=e^{i\phi/2}-e^{2i\phi}/4$
\end_inset 

, of course.
 Next, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(c)$
\end_inset 

 represents a fixed-point of the Mandelbrot iterator: 
\begin_inset Formula $A(c)=A^{2}(c)+c$
\end_inset 

.
 Indeed, this should not be a surprise: the divergent term of the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{c}(t)$
\end_inset 

 is in effect the average over over all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset 

.
 Inside the main bulb, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}z_{n}=A(c)$
\end_inset 

, and so of necessity, the leading divergence of the sum must be 
\begin_inset Formula $A(c)$
\end_inset 

.
 Similarly, in the large bud on the left, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset 

 converges to a two-cycle, with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}\rightarrow1/2+i\sqrt{c+3/4}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n+1}\rightarrow-1/2-i\sqrt{c+3/4}$
\end_inset 

.
 The average of these two values is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset 

, and so we can trivially deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow0^{+}}tS_{c}(t)=-1/2$
\end_inset 

 and thus that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow0^{+}}t|S_{c}(t)|=1/2$
\end_inset 

 which exactly mathes our numerical results.
 In other buds, the sequence converges to m-cycles.
 Thus, in other buds, the divergent term will be the average over these
 m values of the limit cycle.
 Provided one can calculate this average, then one has an exact expression
 for the divergences of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{c}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 Of course, there are considerable additional difficulties once one gets
 into the more contorted parts of the M-set, since the convergence to a
 limit cycle can be extremely slow, thus creating considerable topological
 difficulties when reasoning about the topology of the M-set and in particular,
 the validity of the expansion of terms in the formula 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:term expansion}

\end_inset 

.
 The remainder of this monograph concerns itself with the issue of the rate
 of convergence to the limit cycles, which we will find is given by the
 Dedekind eta.
